05590nam a2200793Ia 9781501738340DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018047979  a97815017383407 a10.1515/97815017383402doi  a(DE-B1597)527379  a(OCoLC)1065782580  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHV5840.A3bB73 2019 4aHV5840.A3bB73 2020 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a364.13365095812231 aBradford, James Tharin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoppies, Politics, and Power :bAfghanistan and the Global History of Drugs and Diplomacy /cJames Tharin Bradford. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (300 p.) :b8 b&w halftones, 1 map, 1 chart  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Colonial and Global Engagements: Afghan Opium on the Periphery of the Global Drug Market -- t2. The Politics of Prohibition: How Diplomacy with the United States Shifted the Drug Control Paradigm in Afghanistan -- t3. The Consequences of Coercion in Badakhshan: The 1958 Prohibition of Opium and the Issue of Culture in Drug Control Policy -- t4. East Meets West: Hippies, Hash, and the Globalization of the Afghan Drug Trade -- t5. The Afghan Connection: Smuggling, Heroin, and Nixon’s War on Drugs in Afghanistan -- t6. All Goods Are Dangerous Goods: Development, the Global Market, and Opium in the Helmand Valley, Afghanistan -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistorians have long neglected Afghanistan's broader history when portraying the opium industry. But in Poppies, Politics, and Power, James Tharin Bradford rebalances the discourse, showing that it is not the past forty years of lawlessness that makes the opium industry what it is, but the sheer breadth of the twentieth-century Afghanistan experience. Rather than byproducts of a failed contemporary system, argues Bradford, drugs, especially opium, were critical components in the formation and failure of the Afghan state.In this history of drugs and drug control in Afghanistan, Bradford shows us how the country moved from licit supply of the global opium trade to one of the major suppliers of hashish and opium through changes in drug control policy shaped largely by the outside force of the United States. Poppies, Politics, and Power breaks the conventional modes of national histories that fail to fully encapsulate the global nature of the drug trade. By providing a global history of opium within the borders of Afghanistan, Bradford demonstrates that the country's drug trade and the government's position on that trade were shaped by the global illegal market and international efforts to suppress it. By weaving together this global history of the drug trade and drug policy with the formation of the Afghan state and issues within Afghan political culture, Bradford completely recasts the current Afghan, and global, drug trade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDrug controlzAfghanistanxHistory. 0aDrug trafficzAfghanistanxHistory. 0aOpium tradezAfghanistanxHistory. 4aAsian Studies. 4aDiplomatic History. 4aInternational Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aopium production, Afghanistan, prohibition, tewntieth-century Afghansitan experience, Afghan state.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-D